shared_text:
Onlyincbus
August 11 at 6:04 PM Â·

ğŸš¨B E A D V I S E DğŸš¨
Columbus has issued a boil water advisory for Downtown and others sections of the city.
The city of Columbus has issued a boil alert advisory because of a power outage at the Dublin Road water plant.
Water customers in the following area are advised to bring all water used for cooking and drinking to a rolling boil for one minute until further notice:

This also could cause discolored water and potentially a temporary increase in lead levels in the water. As a standard practice, the U.S.Environmental Protection Agency recommends doing this to reduce possible lead exposure in drinking water:
If the water has not been used for several hours, run the tap until there is a noticeable temperature drop. Then, run water for 30 seconds to three minutes before using it for drinking and cooking.
Use cold water for cooking, drinking, and preparing baby formula. Boiling the water will not reduce lead.
Clean your faucet aerator.
If water customers have questions, call 614-645-8276.

Thanks for the help with this one @1000jonathans & @columbusdispatch

post_text: CHATA got a little sprucing over the last month! We are so thankful to Community Refugee and Immigration Services for donating this beautiful piece of art to our school! We are deeply committed to ensuring that every member of our community feels seen and appreciated. This mural will be the perfect reminder of that commitment to each and every member of our community. ğŸ–ŒğŸ¨
shared_text:
Jeremy Hollon
June 24 at 4:11 PM Â·

Mural painting looks very different these days (PPE, smaller groups with spacing, temperature checks, individual supplies/food and lots of cleaning), but we are so happy we can still give back!

2020 World Refugee Day's motto is "Every Action Counts" which we are trying to do by brightening the walls and messaging at our schools.

We finished this at CHATA to welcome back their students in the fall! And we have another 10 murals already scheduled this year in Westerville, Licking Heights, and CCS. ğŸ¨ğŸ¨ğŸ¨

post_text: 2nd grade Landscape Project! These second graders learned what a landscape is and how to make their own. We started by looking at all different types of scenery and nature. Some landscapes are full of snow and ice while others are lush and green. Some are even filled with sand! Then they learned the three main levels of a landscape which are background, middle ground and foreground. In the background things appear small because we cannot see the details. In the middle things are medium sized in comparison. In the foreground things are quite large because they are close to us and we can see their details. Then students got creative and added all kinds of elements to their work like animals, plants, weather, time of day, houses, and more. We completed the work by using markers and adding patterns to everything to create texture. Students tried to mix similar colors that work in harmony to finish this amazing artwork. ğŸ¨ğŸŒŸğŸŒˆ
